### 1. The Argument to Refute
**The Argument:**
Tongwei made a mistake by entering the module (solar panel) market.

---

### 2. Why this Argument is Wrong

**Reason 1: The "Partner" Era is Over (Defensive Strategy)**
The argument assumes Tongwei’s customers would have stayed loyal. They didn't. Major customers (like Longi) had already started **"Backward Integration"**—building their own silicon factories to stop buying from Tongwei. If Tongwei didn't move downstream to sell modules, it would be squeezed out of the market with no one to buy its silicon. It was a necessary move for survival, not just expansion.

**Reason 2: Total Cost Matters More Than Margin (Cost Leadership)**
They worry about low margins on modules, but they ignore Tongwei’s **Cost Leadership**. Because Tongwei produce the world cheapest raw materials (silicon/cells), it has a great advantage. Even if they make zero profit on the module itself, they still make money on the materials *inside* the module. They can afford to sell cheap modules to gain market share, while competitors who don't have their own raw materials will lose money and go bankrupt.

**Reason 3: Controlling the "Exit" (Channel Power)**
In the current market **oversupply**, power belongs to whoever own the customers, not the factory. By selling modules, Tongwei controls the final sales channel. If they only sell raw materials, they will be stuck with huge inventory whenever downstream demand slows. Making modules guarantees a "route to market" for their upstream production.

---

### 3. My Opinion

Tongwei’s strategy is **smart and necessary**, even if it looks risky in the short term.

In a manufacturing industry where products are similar, the only way to win long-term is to control the **entire value chain**. Tongwei is using its cash reserves from the silicon business to fight a price war in the module market.

This isn't a mistake; it is a **consolidation strategy**. By keeping prices low, Tongwei is forcing weaker players out of the game. While this hurts profit margins today, it secures Tongwei’s position as one of the few surviving "Super-Integrators" that will dominate the market in the future.